vectorData.altText: 13. The anterior aspect of the hard palate receives sensory innervation from the ___________ nerve, a branch of the maxillary nerve, V2.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That's right!  The nasopalatine branch of maxillary nerve provides sensory innervation to the anterior aspect of the hard palate.

Like almost all structures inferior to the eyes and superior to the oral fissure, including the skin of the face, the general sensory innervation to the palate and maxillary teeth comes from branches of the maxillary nerve, V2. 
The greater (A) and lesser (B) palatine branches of the maxillary nerve     reach the palate from the pterygopalatine fossa (C) by descending through the palatine canal to emerge through the greater (C) and lesser (D) palatine foramina in the palatine bone. The greater palatine nerve supplies the hard palate, and the lesser palatine nerve supplies the soft palate.
The nasopalatine branch of the maxillary nerve (E) reaches the anterior part of the palate from the nasal septum, by passing through the incisive canal (F). 
Blood supply to the palate is from the palatine branches of the maxillary artery (G) which travel with the palatine nerves.
a.k.a. greater and lesser palatine nerves
